From 2641acbe352aaffc208ce02f78ac97136ca631e6 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: czoli1976 <64466170+czoli1976@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Fri, 1 May 2026 14:46:57 +0100
Subject: [PATCH] core/einsum: lower K=1 contractions as broadcast Mul
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

When an EinSum's contraction product is statically 1 (every k-like axis
has shape 1 in both inputs, or no k-like axis exists), detect_rule used
to push it through the OptMatMul pipeline anyway. The GEMM kernel then
ran one FMA per output tile against fixed per-tile setup (clear,
panel-load, store), so the kernel preamble dominated runtime even though
no real matmul work was happening.

This case is reachable in practice. DeepFilterNet 3's erb_dec.onnx ends
in two depthwise ConvTransposes whose 1xN kernel collapses to a per-
channel scalar broadcast: each lowers to gmk,Ngnk->Ngmn with k=1. On
M-series macOS the resulting OptMatMuls were ~7.4 ms and ~3.9 ms — a
combined 50%+ of the decoder, despite doing one multiply per element.

The fix adds a short-circuit before the EinSumMatMul construction: if
all k-like axes are size 1 in both inputs, drop them, align the
remaining axes to the output order with AxisOp::Add/Move/Rm, and wire a
broadcast Mul instead. Inputs are cast up to operating_dt first so the
output type still matches what EinSum::output_facts promises (relevant
for the dequantized i8 -> i32 path that runs through detect_rule again).

Quantized EinSums (q_params=Some) are left to the existing dequant path
in EinSumMatMul::codegen, which produces a non-q EinSum that this rule
then catches naturally.

erb_dec.onnx end-to-end on M-series macOS: 20.3 ms -> 9.7 ms (-52%).
The two ConvTranspose einsums go from 7.4 ms / 3.9 ms to 0.22 ms /
0.11 ms. Output is bit-exact against the unmodified pipeline.
